item.label: Arachnoid membrane
item.name: Arachnoid membrane
item.description: The arachnoid is one of three meningeal layers associated with the brain and spinal cord. It is located between the dura mater and pia mater. The space between the arachnoid and pia is filled with cerebrospinal fluid and contains a trabecular network connecting the arachnoid with the pia.

item.label: Olfactory tracts
item.name: Olfactory tracts
item.description: Located on the ventral surface of the orbital gyri of the frontal lobe, the olfactory tract consists of the axons of the olfactory bulb neurons. These axons branch into the medial and lateral olfactory stria forming the olfactory trigone; they will terminate in the olfactory (piriform) cerebral cortex as well as the amygdala.

item.label: Visual pathway, Optic nerve
item.name: Optic n.
item.description: The Optic nerve or Cranial Nerve II consists of the axons of ganglion cells in the retina. The optic nerve axons will travel through the optic tract and then synapse in the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus as well as in the pretectum.  Between the optic nerve and lateral geniculate nucleus, the nerve fibers from the nasal half of the retina cross the midline in the optic chiasm and then enter the optic tract; the nerve fibers from the temporal half of the retina do not cross, but enter the optic tract directly.

item.label: Infundibular stalk
item.name: Infundibular stalk
item.description: The infundibulum is the hollow, funnel-like stalk of the pituitary gland or hypophysis. It extends from the medial eminence of the hypothalamus to the posterior lobe of the pituitary. Embryologicaly, it and the posterior pituitary are derived from a ventral outgrowth of the diencephalon.

item.label: Interpeduncular cistern
item.name: Interpeduncular cistern
item.description: The interpeduncular cistern is a cerebrospinal fluid-filled subarachnoid space located between the cerebral peduncles on the inferior surface of the midbrain, i.e. the interpeduncular fossa, and extending rostrally beneath the diencephalon.

item.label: Vertebral artery
item.name: Vertebral a.
item.description: Along with the internal carotid arteries, the vertebral arteries are the major blood supply to the brain. The two vertebral arteries fuse at the junction of the medulla and pons to form the basilar artery. The vertebral-basilar system supplies structures in the posterior fossa plus posterior aspects of the diencephalon, choroid plexus in the third and lateral ventricles and the medial and inferior surfaces of the occipital and temporal lobes of the cerebral hemispheres.

item.label: Posterior inferior cerebellar artery
item.name: Posterior inferior cerebe
item.description: The posterior inferior cerebellar artery is AKA the PICA.  It is a branch from the vertebral artery near its junction with the basilar artery. It supplies much of the inferior surface of the cerebellar hemispheres but very importantly, it supplies several functionally important structures on the dorsal lateral aspect of the medulla. Loss of this blood supply results in the PICA or lateral medullary syndrome.

item.label: Basilar artery
item.name: Basilar a.
item.description: The two vertebral arteries fuse at the junction of the medulla and pons to form the basilar artery. At the junction of the pons and midbrain, the basilar bifurcates into two terminal branches, the posterior cerebral arteries. Branches of the basilar & posterior cerebral arteries supply parts of the brain stem, cerebellum, posterior aspects of the diencephalon, choroid plexus in the third and lateral ventricles and the medial and inferior surfaces of the occipital and temporal lobes of the cerebral hemispheres.

item.label: Anterior inferior cerebellar artery
item.name: Anterior inferior cerebel
item.description: The anterior inferior cerebellar artery [AICA] is a branch from the basilar artery just rostral to where the two vertebral arteries unite to form the basilar. It supplies the more anterior portions of the inferior surface of the cerebellum such as the flocculus plus parts of the caudal pons.

item.label: Internal carotid artery
item.name: Internal carotid a.
item.description: With the verbebral arteries, the internal carotid arteries provide the blood supply to the brain. The internal carotid branches from the common carotid in the neck and enters the base of the skull via the carotid canal. As it enters the Circle of Willis, it divides into its two terminal branches: the middle and anterior cerebral arteries.
